def longest_substring_with_two_distinct(s):
    # Dictionary to store character counts within the window
    char_count = {}
    left, max_length = 0, 0
    start_index_of_max = 0

    for right in range(len(s)):
        # Add current character to dictionary or increment its count
        if s[right] in char_count:
            char_count[s[right]] += 1
        else:
            char_count[s[right]] = 1

        # If more than two distinct characters, shrink the window from left
        while len(char_count) > 2:
            char_count[s[left]] -= 1
            if char_count[s[left]] == 0:
                del char_count[s[left]]
            left += 1

        # Update max length and starting index if current window is larger
        if right - left + 1 > max_length:
            max_length = right - left + 1
            start_index_of_max = left

    # Return the length and substring of the longest valid window
    return max_length, s[start_index_of_max:start_index_of_max+max_length]
```

This implementation uses a sliding window approach with two pointers (left and right) to maintain a window that contains at most two distinct characters. A dictionary `char_count` is used to keep track of character frequencies within the current window. When more than two distinct characters are found, the left pointer is moved to shrink the window until it contains only one or two distinct characters again. The length and starting index of the longest valid window are updated whenever a larger window is found.

